# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: samtools-bam
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] The **BAM file format** (which stands for **Binary Alignment Map**) is the lossless, compressed binary representation of a Sequence Alignment Map file.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] It is compressed by BGZF library and supports fast, random access.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] BAM is one of the most common file formats for raw genome sequencing data.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] BAM is the compressed binary representation of SAM (Sequence Alignment Map), a compact and index-able representation of nucleotide sequence alignments.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] The goal of indexing is to retrieve alignments that overlap a specific location quickly without having to go through all of them.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] Before indexing, BAM must be sorted by reference ID and then leftmost coordinate.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] BAM format uses 0-based coordinate system, where as SAM uses 1-based coordinate system.
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] BAM can represent values in the range [−2^31 , 2^32).
[src:samtools-bam/binary-alignment-map] To view a list of sequencing and analysis tools that work with SAM/BAM click here.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] It was originally developed at the Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute to bundle a FASTA formatted sequence and its quality data, but has become the *de facto* standard for storing the output of high-throughput sequencing instruments such as the Illumina Genome Analyzer.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The byte representing quality runs from 0x21 (lowest quality; '!' in ASCII) to 0x7e (highest quality; '~' in ASCII).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The original Sanger FASTQ files split long sequences and quality strings over multiple lines, as is typically done for FASTA files.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Accounting for this makes parsing more complicated due to the choice of "@" and "+" as markers (as these characters can also occur in the quality string).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Multi-line FASTQ files (and consequently multi-line FASTQ parsers) are less common now that the majority of sequencing carried out is short-read Illumina sequencing, with typical sequence lengths of around 100bp.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Versions of the Illumina pipeline since 1.4 appear to use **#NNNNNN** instead of **#0** for the multiplex ID, where **NNNNNN** is the sequence of the multiplex tag.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Note that more recent versions of Illumina software output a sample number (defined by the order of the samples in the sample sheet) in place of an index sequence when an index sequence is not explicitly specified for a sample in the sample sheet.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] FASTQ files from the INSDC Sequence Read Archive often include a description, e.g.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] In this example there is an NCBI-assigned identifier, and the description holds the original identifier from Solexa/Illumina (as described above) plus the read length.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Sequencing was performed in paired-end mode (~500bp insert size), see SRR001666.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The default output format of fastq-dump produces entire spots, containing any technical reads and typically single or paired-end biological reads.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] When present in the archive, fastq-dump can attempt to restore read names to original format.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] In the example above, the original read names were used rather than the accessioned read name.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] NCBI accessions runs and the reads they contain.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Original read names, assigned by sequencers, are able to function as locally unique identifiers of a read, and convey exactly as much information as a serial number.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The ids above were algorithmically assigned based upon run information and geometric coordinates.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Early SRA loaders parsed these ids and stored their decomposed components internally.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] NCBI stopped recording read names because they are frequently modified from the vendors' original format in order to associate some additional information meaningful to a particular processing pipeline, and this caused name format violations that resulted in a high number of rejected submissions.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Without a clear schema for read names, their function remains that of a unique read id, conveying the same amount of information as a read serial number.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] See various SRA Toolkit issues for details and discussions.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Also note that fastq-dump converts this FASTQ data from the original Solexa/Illumina encoding to the Sanger standard (see encodings below).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] This is because the SRA serves as a repository for NGS information, rather than format.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The various *-dump tools are capable of producing data in several formats from the same source.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The requirements for doing so have been dictated by users over several years, with the majority of early demand coming from the 1000 Genomes Project.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] A quality value *Q* is an integer mapping of *p* (i.e., the probability that the corresponding base call is incorrect).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Two different equations have been in use.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Although both mappings are asymptotically identical at higher quality values, they differ at lower quality levels (i.e., approximately *p* > 0.05, or equivalently, *Q* < 13).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] At times there has been disagreement about which mapping Illumina actually uses.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The user guide (Appendix B, page 122) for version 1.4 of the Illumina pipeline states that: "The scores are defined as ⁠ $Q=10\cdot \log _{10}{\tfrac {p}{1-p}}$ ⁠ [*sic*], where p is the probability of a base call corresponding to the base in question".
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] In retrospect, this entry in the manual appears to have been an error.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The user guide (What's New, page 5) for version 1.5 of the Illumina pipeline lists this description instead: "Important Changes in Pipeline v1.3 [*sic*].
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The quality scoring scheme has changed to the Phred [i.e., Sanger] scoring scheme, encoded as an ASCII character by adding 64 to the Phred value.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] A Phred score of a base is: $Q_{\text{phred}}=-10\log _{10}e$ , where *e* is the estimated probability of a base being wrong.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] An alternative interpretation of this ASCII encoding has been proposed.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Also, in Illumina runs using PhiX controls, the character 'B' was observed to represent an "unknown quality score".
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The error rate of 'B' reads was roughly 3 phred scores lower the mean observed score of a given run.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] For raw reads, the range of scores will depend on the technology and the base caller used, but will typically be up to 41 for recent Illumina chemistry.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Since the maximum observed quality score was previously only 40, various scripts and tools break when they encounter data with quality values larger than 40.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] For processed reads, scores may be even higher.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] For example, quality values of 45 are observed in reads from Illumina's Long Read Sequencing Service (previously Moleculo).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] This format matched the different sequencing chemistry used by SOLiD sequencers.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Initial representations only used nucleotide bases at the start of the sequence, but later versions included bases embedded at periodic intervals to improve basecalling and mapping accuracy.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The quality values for CSFASTQ are identical to those of the Sanger format.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Alignment tools differ in their preferred version of the quality values: some include a quality score (set to 0, i.e.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] '!') for the leading nucleotide, others do not.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The sequence read archive includes this quality score.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The FAST4 format was invented as a derivative of the FASTQ format where each of the 4 bases (A,C,G,T) had separate probabilities stored.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] It was part of the Swift basecaller, an open source package for primary data analysis on next-gen sequence data "from images to basecalls".
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The FAST5 format was invented as an extension of the FAST4 format.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The FAST5 files are Hierarchical Data Format 5 (HDF5) files with a specific schema defined by Oxford Nanopore Technologies (ONT).
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] FASTQ read simulation has been approached by several tools.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] A comparison of those tools can be seen here.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] General-purpose tools such as Gzip and bzip2 regard FASTQ as a plain text file and result in suboptimal compression ratios.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] NCBI's Sequence Read Archive encodes metadata using the LZ-77 scheme.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] General FASTQ compressors typically compress distinct fields (read names, sequences, comments, and quality scores) in a FASTQ file separately; these include DSRC and DSRC2, FQC, LFQC, Fqzcomp, and Slimfastq.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] When the coverage or the repeat content of the sequenced genome is high, this leads to a high compression ratio.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Unlike the SAM/BAM formats, FASTQ files do not specify a reference genome.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] **Alignment-based FASTQ compressors** supports the use of either user-provided or *de novo* assembled reference: LW-FQZip uses a provided reference genome and Quip, Leon, k-Path and KIC perform ***de novo*** assembly using a de Bruijn graph-based approach.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Explicit read mapping and *de novo* assembly are typically slow.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] **Reordering-based FASTQ compressors** first cluster reads that share long substrings and then independently compress reads in each cluster after reordering them or assembling them into longer contigs, achieving perhaps the best trade-off between the running time and compression rate.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] SCALCE is the first such tool, followed by Orcom and Mince.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] BEETL uses a generalized Burrows–Wheeler transform for reordering reads, and HARC achieves better performance with hash-based reordering.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] AssemblTrie instead assembles reads into reference trees with as few total number of symbols as possible in the reference.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Benchmarks for these tools are available.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Quality values account for about half of the required disk space in the FASTQ format (before compression), and therefore the compression of the quality values can significantly reduce storage requirements and speed up analysis and transmission of sequencing data.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Both lossless and lossy compression are recently being considered in the literature.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] For example, the algorithm QualComp performs lossy compression with a rate (number of bits per quality value) specified by the user.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Based on rate-distortion theory results, it allocates the number of bits so as to minimize the MSE (mean squared error) between the original (uncompressed) and the reconstructed (after compression) quality values.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Other algorithms for compression of quality values include SCALCE and Fastqz.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] Both are lossless compression algorithms that provide an optional controlled lossy transformation approach.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] For example, SCALCE reduces the alphabet size based on the observation that “neighboring” quality values are similar in general.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] As of the HiSeq 2500 Illumina gives the option to output qualities that have been coarse grained into quality bins.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] The binned scores are computed directly from the empirical quality score table, which is itself tied to the hardware, software and chemistry that were used during the sequencing experiment.
[src:samtools-bam/fastq-format] There is no standard file extension for a FASTQ file, but .fq and .fastq are commonly used.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] A **Phred quality score** is a measure of the quality of the identification of the nucleobases generated by automated DNA sequencing.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] It was originally developed for the computer program Phred to help in the automation of DNA sequencing in the Human Genome Project.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred quality scores are assigned to each nucleotide base call in automated sequencer traces.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] The FASTQ format encodes phred scores as ASCII characters alongside the read sequences.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred quality scores have become widely accepted to characterize the quality of DNA sequences, and can be used to compare the efficacy of different sequencing methods.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Perhaps the most important use of Phred quality scores is the automatic determination of accurate, quality-based consensus sequences.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] For example, if Phred assigns a quality score of 30 to a base, the chances that this base is called incorrectly are 1 in 1000.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] The phred quality score is the negative ratio of the error probability to the reference level of $P=1$ expressed in Decibel (dB).
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] The idea of sequence quality scores can be traced back to the original description of the SCF file format by Rodger Staden's group in 1992.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] In 1995, Bonfield and Staden proposed a method to use base-specific quality scores to improve the accuracy of consensus sequences in DNA sequencing projects.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] However, early attempts to develop base-specific quality scores had only limited success.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] The first program to develop accurate and powerful base-specific quality scores was the program Phred.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred was able to calculate highly accurate quality scores that were logarithmically linked to the error probabilities.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred was quickly adopted by all the major genome sequencing centers as well as many other laboratories; the vast majority of the DNA sequences produced during the Human Genome Project were processed with Phred.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] After Phred quality scores became the required standard in DNA sequencing, other manufacturers of DNA sequencing instruments, including Li-Cor and ABI, developed similar quality scoring metrics for their base calling software.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred's approach to base calling and calculating quality scores was outlined by Ewing *et al.*.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] To determine quality scores, Phred first calculates several parameters related to peak shape and peak resolution at each base.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred then uses these parameters to look up a corresponding quality score in huge lookup tables.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] These lookup tables were generated from sequence traces where the correct sequence was known, and are hard coded in Phred; different lookup tables are used for different sequencing chemistries and machines.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] An evaluation of the accuracy of Phred quality scores for a number of variations in sequencing chemistry and instrumentation showed that Phred quality scores are highly accurate.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred was originally developed for "slab gel" sequencing machines like the ABI373.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] When originally developed, Phred had a lower base calling error rate than the manufacturer's base calling software, which also did not provide quality scores.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] However, Phred was only partially adapted to the capillary DNA sequencers that became popular later.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] In contrast, instrument manufacturers like ABI continued to adapt their base calling software changes in sequencing chemistry, and have included the ability to create Phred-like quality scores.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Therefore, the need to use Phred for base calling of DNA sequencing traces has diminished, and using the manufacturer's current software versions can often give more accurate results.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phred quality scores are used for assessment of sequence quality, recognition and removal of low-quality sequence (end clipping), and determination of accurate consensus sequences.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Originally, Phred quality scores were primarily used by the sequence assembly program Phrap.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phrap was routinely used in some of the largest sequencing projects in the Human Genome Sequencing Project and is currently one of the most widely used DNA sequence assembly programs in the biotech industry.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phrap uses Phred quality scores to determine highly accurate consensus sequences and to estimate the quality of the consensus sequences.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phrap also uses Phred quality scores to estimate whether discrepancies between two overlapping sequences are more likely to arise from random errors, or from different copies of a repeated sequence.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Within the Human Genome Project, the most important use of Phred quality scores was for automatic determination of consensus sequences.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Before Phred and Phrap, scientists had to carefully look at discrepancies between overlapping DNA fragments; often, this involved manual determination of the highest-quality sequence, and manual editing of any errors.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Phrap's use of Phred quality scores effectively automated finding the highest-quality consensus sequence; in most cases, this completely circumvents the need for any manual editing.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] As a result, the estimated error rate in assemblies that were created automatically with Phred and Phrap is typically substantially lower than the error rate of manually edited sequence.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] In 2009, many commonly used software packages make use of Phred quality scores, albeit to a different extent.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Programs like Sequencher use quality scores for display, end clipping, and consensus determination; other programs like CodonCode Aligner also implement quality-based consensus methods.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Quality scores are normally stored together with the nucleotide sequence in the widely accepted FASTQ format.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] They account for about half of the required disk space in the FASTQ format (before compression), and therefore the compression of the quality values can significantly reduce storage requirements and speed up analysis and transmission of sequencing data.
[src:samtools-bam/phred-quality-score] Other algorithms for compression of quality values include SCALCE, Fastqz and more recently QVZ, AQUa and the MPEG-G standard, that is currently under development by the MPEG standardisation working group.
[src:samtools-bam/pileup-format] If present, the ASCII value of the character minus 33 gives the mapping Phred quality of each of the bases in the previous column 5.
[src:samtools-bam/pileup-format] This is similar to quality encoding in the FASTQ format.
[src:samtools-bam/pileup-format] There is no standard file extension for a Pileup file, but .msf (multiple sequence file), .pup and .pileup are used.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The SAM format consists of a header and an alignment section.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The binary equivalent of a SAM file is a Binary Alignment Map (BAM) file, which stores the same data in a compressed binary representation.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] SAM files can be analysed and edited with the software SAMtools.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The header section, if present, must precede the alignment section.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] Headings begin with the '@' symbol, which distinguishes them from the alignment section.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] Alignment sections have 11 mandatory fields, as well as a variable number of optional fields.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] RNAME: Reference sequence NAME of the alignment.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If @SQ header lines are present, RNAME (if not ‘*’) must be present in one of the SQ-SN tag.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] An unmapped segment without coordinate has a ‘*’ at this field.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] However, an unmapped segment may also have an ordinary coordinate such that it can be placed at a desired position after sorting.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If RNAME is ‘*’, no assumptions can be made about POS and CIGAR.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] POS: 1-based leftmost mapping POSition of the first matching base.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The first base in a reference sequence has coordinate 1.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] POS is set as 0 for an unmapped read without coordinate.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If POS is 0, no assumptions can be made about RNAME and CIGAR.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] It equals −10 log10 Pr{mapping position is wrong}, rounded to the nearest integer.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] A value 255 indicates that the mapping quality is not available.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] CIGAR: Concise Idiosyncratic Gapped Alignment Report (CIGAR) string.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] RNEXT: Reference sequence name of the primary alignment of the NEXT read in the template.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] For the last read, the next read is the first read in the template.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If @SQ header lines are present, RNEXT (if not ‘*’ or ‘=’) must be present in one of the SQ-SN tag.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] This field is set as ‘*’ when the information is unavailable, and set as ‘=’ if RNEXT is identical RNAME.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If not ‘=’ and the next read in the template has one primary mapping (see also bit 0x100 in FLAG), this field is identical to RNAME at the primary line of the next read.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If RNEXT is ‘*’, no assumptions can be made on PNEXT and bit 0x20.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] PNEXT: Position of the primary alignment of the NEXT read in the template.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] Set as 0 when the information is unavailable.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] This field equals POS at the primary line of the next read.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If PNEXT is 0, no assumptions can be made on RNEXT and bit 0x20.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If all segments are mapped to the same reference, the unsigned observed template length equals the number of bases from the leftmost mapped base to the rightmost mapped base.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The leftmost segment has a plus sign and the rightmost has a minus sign.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The sign of segments in the middle is undefined.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] It is set as 0 for single-segment template or when the information is unavailable.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] This field can be a ‘*’ when the sequence is not stored.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If not a ‘*’, the length of the sequence must equal the sum of lengths of M/I/S/=/X operations in CIGAR.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] An ‘=’ denotes the base is identical to the reference base.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] No assumptions can be made on the letter cases.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] QUAL: ASCII of base QUALity plus 33 (same as the quality string in the Sanger FASTQ format).
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] A base quality is the phred-scaled base error probability which equals −10 log10 Pr{base is wrong}.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] This field can be a ‘*’ when quality is not stored.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] If not a ‘*’, SEQ must not be a ‘*’ and the length of the quality string ought to equal the length of SEQ.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] The FLAG field is displayed as a single integer, but is the sum of bitwise flags to denote multiple attributes of a read alignment.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] Each attribute denotes one bit in the binary representation of the integer.
[src:samtools-bam/sam-file-format] It may be a single value or **B** (general array).
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Like many Unix commands, SAMtool commands follow a stream model, where data runs through each command as if carried on a conveyor belt.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] This allows combining multiple commands into a data processing pipeline.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Although the final output can be very complex, only a limited number of simple commands are needed to produce it.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] If not specified, the standard streams (stdin, stdout, and stderr) are assumed.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Data sent to stdout are printed to the screen by default but are easily redirected to another file using the normal Unix redirectors (> and >>), or to another command via a pipe (|).
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] command filters SAM or BAM formatted data.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Using options and arguments it understands what data to select (possibly all of it) and passes only that data through.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Input is usually a sam or bam file specified as an argument, but could be sam or bam data piped from any other command.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Possible uses include extracting a subset of data into a new file, converting between BAM and SAM formats, and just looking at the raw file contents.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] The order of extracted reads is preserved.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] command sorts a BAM file based on its position in the reference, as determined by its alignment.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] The element + coordinate in the reference that the first matched base in the read aligns to is used as the key to order it by. [TODO: verify].
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] The sorted output is dumped to a new file by default, although it can be directed to stdout (using the -o option).
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] As sorting is memory intensive and BAM files can be large, this command supports a sectioning mode (with the -m options) to use at most a given amount of memory and generate multiple output file.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] command creates a new index file that allows fast look-up of data in a (sorted) SAM or BAM.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] file allows programs that can read it to more efficiently work with the data in the associated files.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] command starts an interactive ascii-based viewer that can be used to visualize how reads are aligned to specified small regions of the reference genome.
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] Within the view, it is possible to jumping to different positions along reference elements (using 'g') and display help information ('?').
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] (or BCF) file giving, for each genomic coordinate, the overlapping read bases and indels at that position in the input BAM files(s).
[src:samtools-bam/samtools] This can be used for SNP calling for example.
